  "texts": [
    "For instance, in Recital 84the DSA mandates that VLOPs pay \"particular attention to how their services are utilized to disseminate or amplify misleading or deceptive content, including disinformation\".",
    "This broader classification of harmful content extends beyond disinformation to a more general category of misleading or deceptive content, which could therefore be seen to also include misinformation.",
    "Appendix 2: The EU Digital Services Act framework and aimsThis section provides an overview of the DSA, including its context, mechanisms, and expected impacts, to situate the need for rigorous research evaluating its efficacy.",
    "Overview of Digital Services ActThe DSA establishes an extensive set of obligations and accountability mechanisms for online intermediaries aimed at addressing illegal and harmful content at scale.",
    "It represents a major evolution in the EU's platform governance approach beyond previous self-regulatory initiatives like the 2018 Code of Practice on Disinformation [46].We can see how the EU Commission's Assessment of the Code of Practice [49] reveals some of its shortcomings, such as inconsistent application of the Code across platforms and Member States, together with limitations due to the self-regulatory nature of the Code and its lack of extensive coverage."
